The paper deals with activity detection in video streams, which is a problem that falls under computer vision. Therefore, cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also introduces a new model that is trained end-to-end, which involves machine learning techniques, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) another likely sub-category. The model also uses convolutional features, which is a common technique in multimedia analysis, making cs.MM (Multimedia) another possible sub-category. The paper also involves classification and optimization techniques, which are common in artificial intelligence, making cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) another possible sub-category. Finally, the paper involves the evaluation of the model on different datasets, which involves information retrieval techniques, making cs.IR (Information Retrieval) another possible sub-category.
